title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory M1 Garand WWII 1942 Matching
postcontent: This Springfield Armory M1 Grand was born September 1942. Guadalcanal Operation Watchtower had begun just a month prior. The Japanese had suffered major setbacks at Coral Sea and Midway. Operation Torch, North African Campaign was still in the planning stages. By the looks of this weapon, I doubt if it was in service for anything after that either. I am just a casual WWII historian so I bought Scott Duff's book; The M1 Garand World War II. The barrel date matches the serial number. The internal parts are properly marked for the manufacturer and date of this weapon. I took numerous photos so you can judge for yourself. The bore is clean with deep rifling. title: For Sale:  L.C. Smith Ideal Grade 20 Gauge - 30" BARRELS EJECTORS, 97% CASE COLOR
postcontent: Smith is the first level of a "graded" Elsie, with open foliate engraving pattern, nicer wood and checkering than the Field grade, and the banjo style forend latch rather than a snap-on forend. They made around 3659 Ideal Grades in 20ga., so it is not a "rare" gun. However, only 426 were made with the long, graceful 30" barrels, and only 1/2, or about 210 total of those were made with ejectors. So this combination is a very hard gun to find. Add to the low production numbers the HIGH, FACTORY ORIGINAL CONDITION AND DESIRABLE FEATURES AND LIGHT WEIGHT and you have an incredible find in the vintage gun world. Some Elsies have a delicate balance making you believe they are true lightweight guns. Weighing 6lbs 6oz. and balanced 3/8" ahead of the hinge pin, I was surprised when I put her on the scale. I would have guessed 6lbs. she felt so perfect in hand, not at all barrel heavy. In 1927 it was made with more care than some of the later guns that felt so clunky with the tall rib. The case color is 97% and vivid, the screws are near perfect, and the wood to metal fit is superb, with no cracks or splits at the apex of the locks............
